  "body": "Naismith's rule Naismith's rule is used by runners and walkers to estimate journey times in hilly terrain. In 1892, Naismith wrote in the Scottish Mountaineering Club Journal that a person “in fair condition should allow for easy expeditions an hour for every three miles on the map, with an additional hour for every 2000 feet of ascent.” (Source: Scarf, 1998)  According to Naismith, one unit of ascent requires the same time as how many units of horizontal travel? (Convert miles to feet.) This is called Naismith's number . Round your answer to one decimal place  A walk in the Brecon Beacons in Wales covers kilometers horizontally and climbs meters. What is the equivalent flat distance?  If you can walk at a pace of minutes per kilometer over flat ground, how long will the walk in the Brecon Beacons take?   "
